{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fd306bc8-475d-4cf1-9845-7c195a284c8b","content":"Here's what breaks in each case and how to fix it:\n\n---\n\n**1. SpanHelper.cs — stricter ref-safety escape analysis**\n\nC# 15 tightens span safety rules. The collection expression `[x * 2]` can produce a stack-allocated span scoped to the loop body. Assigning it to `results` (declared *outside* the loop) is a dangling-reference hazard — the backing storage dies at each iteration's end. C# 14's analysis missed this; C# 15 rejects it.\n\n**Fix** — accumulate into a `List<int>` instead:\n\n```csharp\npublic static int[] ProcessItems(int[] source)\n{\n    var results = new List<int>();\n    foreach (var x in source)\n        results.Add(x * 2);\n    return results.ToArray();\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. Metadata.cs — `this` disallowed in `nameof` inside attributes**\n\nC# 14 let `nameof` reference instance members in attribute arguments via their *unqualified* name, but `this` itself is not valid in an attribute context (no instance exists). C# 15 now enforces this strictly — `nameof(this.Endpoint)` errors because `this` is unavailable, even though `nameof` never evaluates it.\n\n**Fix** — drop the `this` qualifier:\n\n```csharp\n[System.Obsolete(nameof(Endpoint))]\nvoid LegacyConnect() { }\n```\n\n---\n\n**3. Pipeline.cs — `with` contextual-keyword collision in collection expressions**\n\n`with` has been a contextual keyword since C# 9 (record `with` expressions). In C# 15, collection expressions now recognize `with` syntactically, so `[with(x, y), z]` is parsed as the start of a `with` expression, not a method call — producing a syntax error.\n\n**Fix** — use the verbatim identifier `@with`, or rename the method:\n\n```csharp\nobject[] items = [@with(x, y), z];\n// or, better:\nobject Combine(object a, object b) => (a, b);\nobject[] items = [Combine(x, y), z];\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"807806db-2cda-4858-afcd-69568b4679b5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":