're implying this code worked before. Let me think through the actual rules here. In C# 13, `nameof` was extended to allow unqualified instance member names in attributes, so `nameof(Endpoint)` would work. But explicitly qualifying it with `this` might never have been valid since `this` isn't available in attribute argument contexts. I need to verify whether `nameof(this.Endpoint)` was ever actually allowed or if the user's code has a different issue. I'm realizing the actual problem: in C# 15, when `with(x, y)` appears inside a collection expression like `[with(x, y), z]`, the parser might misinterpret it as a `with` expression syntax rather than a method call, or `with` could become a reserved keyword in that context, causing a parsing conflict.\n\nThe solution would be to either rename the method, use the verbatim identifier `@with(x, y)`, or call it through a different syntax. But stepping back, there are likely multiple issues at play here. One involves span reassignment across scopes—C# 15 probably tightened ref safety rules, so assigning a span from a narrower scope (especially one using collection expressions with potential stack allocation) to an outer scope variable would now be flagged as unsafe. The fix there would be switching to a `List<int>` or pre-allocating an array. Another issue could be with `nameof(this.Endpoint)` in attributes, where C# 15 may have restricted using explicit `this` in that context, requiring just `nameof(Endpoint)` instead.\n\nI should be honest though—C# 15 and .NET 11 would be released around November 2026, which is beyond my training data cutoff in early 2025. I can't be certain about the exact changes, but I can reason through what's likely based on the language's design trajectory and what the user is describing as a real scenario they're encountering. I need to reconsider my approach here—C# 15 and .NET 11 haven't actually been released yet as of my training cutoff, so I don't have concrete information about breaking chang